04210nam a22004935i 9780773556461DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735564617 a10.1515/97807735564612doi  a(DE-B1597)654778  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHM883b.L58 2019 7aNAT0110002bisacsh04a303.48/4097112231 aLittle, J.I., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAt the Wilderness Edge :bThe Rise of the Antidevelopment Movement on Canada's West Coast /cJ.I. Little. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b11 photos, 5 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Rural, Wildland, and Resource Studies ;v1100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t“One of the finest pieces of empty real estate in Canada”: The Creation of Devonian Harbour Park, 1963–83 -- t“The greatest playground in the entire Dominion”: Defending Hollyburn Ridge, 1932–76 -- t“Restful Refuge” or “Vancouver’s Bedroom”? The Making of Bowen Island’s First Official Community Plan, 1969–77 -- t“The Newcastle of the Pacific”? Protecting the Squamish Estuary and Howe Sound, 1971–79 -- t“The best use of this island is for recreation”: Resisting the Gambier Island Copper Mine Proposal, 1979–85 -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVancouver prides itself on being a green city, and the west coast is known for its active environmental protest culture. But the roots of this mentality reach far beyond the founding of organizations such as Greenpeace. Small campaigns led by local community groups from the 1960s onward left a lasting impact on the region. At the Wilderness Edge examines five antidevelopment campaigns in and around Vancouver that reflected a dramatic decline in public support for large-scale commercial and industrial projects. J.I. Little describes the highly effective protests that were instrumental in preserving threatened green spaces on Coal Harbour, Hollyburn Ridge, Bowen Island, Gambier Island, and the Squamish estuary, keeping these important British Columbia landmarks from becoming a high-rise development project, a downhill ski resort, a suburban housing tract, an open-pit copper mine, and a major coal port, respectively. Through detailed analysis of development proposals and protests, government studies, and community responses, Little argues that it was not the usual suspects – 1960s radicalism and anti-establishment youth culture – that initiated and carried out these protests, but rather middle-aged, middle-class, politically engaged citizens, many of whom were women. An engaging study of grassroots politics in action, At the Wilderness Edge sheds new light on the rise of environmental consciousness, a pivotal era in the history of British Columbia, the Pacific Northwest, and Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEconomic developmentxSocial aspectszBritish Columbia. 0aGreen movementzBritish Columbia. 0aProtest movementszBritish Columbia. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355646140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773556461423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773556461/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles